# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decoupling-electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:decoupling-electronics/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] In electronics, **biasing** is the setting of DC (direct current) operating conditions (current and voltage) of an electronic component that processes time-varying signals.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Many electronic devices, such as diodes, transistors and vacuum tubes, whose function is processing time-varying (AC) signals, also require a steady (DC) current or voltage at their terminals to operate correctly.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] This current or voltage is called *bias*.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The AC signal applied to them is superposed on this DC bias current or voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The operating point of a device, also known as bias point, **quiescent point**, or **Q-point**, is the DC voltage or current at a specified terminal of an active device (a transistor or vacuum tube) with no input signal applied.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] A **bias circuit** is a portion of the device's circuit that supplies this steady current or voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] In electronics, 'biasing' usually refers to a fixed DC voltage or current applied to a terminal of an electronic component such as a diode, transistor or vacuum tube in a circuit in which AC signals are also present, in order to establish proper operating conditions for the component.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] For example, a bias voltage is applied to a transistor in an electronic amplifier to allow the transistor to operate in a particular region of its transconductance curve.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] For vacuum tubes, a grid bias voltage is often applied to the grid electrodes for the same reason.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] In magnetic tape recording, the term *bias* is also used for a high-frequency signal added to the audio signal and applied to the recording head, to improve the quality of the recording on the tape.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Linear circuits involving transistors typically require specific DC voltages and currents for correct operation, which can be achieved using a biasing circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] As an example of the need for careful biasing, consider a transistor amplifier.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] In linear amplifiers, a small input signal gives a larger output signal without any change in shape (low distortion): the input signal causes the output signal to vary up and down about the Q-point in a manner strictly proportional to the input.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] However, because the relationship between input and output for a transistor is not linear across its full operating range, the transistor amplifier only approximates linear operation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] For low distortion, the transistor must be biased so the output signal swing does not drive the transistor into a region of extremely nonlinear operation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] For a bipolar junction transistor amplifier, this requirement means that the transistor must stay in the active mode, and avoid cut-off or saturation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The same requirement applies to a MOSFET amplifier, although the terminology differs a little: the MOSFET must stay in the active mode, and avoid cutoff or ohmic operation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] For bipolar junction transistors the bias point is chosen to keep the transistor operating in the *active* mode, using a variety of circuit techniques, establishing the Q-point DC voltage and current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] A small signal is then applied on top of the bias.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The Q-point is typically near the middle of the DC load line, so as to obtain the maximum available peak-to-peak signal amplitude without distortion due to clipping as the transistor reaches saturation or cut-off.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The process of obtaining an appropriate DC collector current at a certain DC collector voltage by setting up the operating point is called biasing.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Grid bias is the DC voltage provided at the control grid of a vacuum tube relative to the cathode for the purpose of establishing the zero input signal or steady state operating condition of the tube.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The required bias voltage is usually determined from published vacuum-tube characteristic curves, which show the relationship between plate current, plate voltage, and control-grid voltage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] There are many methods of achieving grid bias.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Combinations of bias methods may be used on the same tube.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The selected bias determines the quiescent operating point of the tube on its characteristic curves and therefore the linearity, gain, and allowable signal swing of the amplifier stage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Electret microphone elements typically include a junction field-effect transistor as an impedance converter to drive other electronics within a few meters of the microphone.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] The operating current of this JFET is typically 0.1 to 0.5 mA and is often referred to as bias, which is different from the phantom power interface, which supplies 48 volts to operate the backplate of a traditional condenser microphone.
[src:decoupling-electronics/biasing] Electret microphone bias is sometimes supplied on a separate conductor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] In electronics, a **common-emitter** amplifier is one of three basic single-stage bipolar-junction-transistor (BJT) amplifier topologies, typically used as a voltage amplifier.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] It offers high current gain (typically 200), medium input resistance and a high output resistance.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The output of a common emitter amplifier is inverted; i.e. for a sine wave input signal, the output signal is 180 degrees out of phase with respect to the input.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] In this circuit, the base terminal of the transistor serves as the input, the collector is the output, and the emitter is *common* to both (for example, it may be tied to ground reference or a power supply rail), hence its name.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The analogous FET circuit is the common-source amplifier, and the analogous tube circuit is the common-cathode amplifier.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Common-emitter amplifiers give the amplifier an inverted output and can have a very high gain that may vary widely from one transistor to the next.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The gain is a strong function of both temperature and bias current, and so the actual gain is somewhat unpredictable.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Stability is another problem associated with such high-gain circuits due to any unintentional positive feedback that may be present.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Other problems associated with the circuit are the low input dynamic range imposed by the small-signal limit; there is high distortion if this limit is exceeded and the transistor ceases to behave like its small-signal model.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] One common way of alleviating these issues is with *emitter degeneration*.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] This refers to the addition of a small resistor between the emitter and the common signal source (e.g., the ground reference or a power supply rail).
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The voltage gain depends almost exclusively on the ratio of the resistors $R_{\text{C}}/R_{\text{E}}$ rather than the transistor's intrinsic and unpredictable characteristics.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The distortion and stability characteristics of the circuit are thus improved at the expense of a reduction in gain.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] At low frequencies and using a simplified hybrid-pi model, the following small-signal characteristics can be derived.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] If the emitter degeneration resistor is not present, then $R_{\text{E}}=0\,\Omega$ , and the expressions effectively simplify to the ones given by the rightmost column (note that the voltage gain is an ideal value; the actual gain is somewhat unpredictable).
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] As expected, when *$R_{\text{E}}\,$* is increased, the input impedance is increased and the voltage gain $A_{\text{v}}\,$ is reduced.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The bandwidth of the common-emitter amplifier tends to be low due to high capacitance resulting from the Miller effect.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The parasitic base-collector capacitance $C_{\text{CB}}\,$ appears like a larger parasitic capacitor $C_{\text{CB}}(1-A_{\text{v}})\,$ (where $A_{\text{v}}\,$ is negative) from the base to ground.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] This large capacitor greatly decreases the bandwidth of the amplifier as it makes the time constant of the parasitic input RC filter $r_{\text{s}}(1-A_{\text{V}})C_{\text{CB}}\,$ where $r_{\text{s}}\,$ is the output impedance of the signal source connected to the ideal base.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The Miller effect negatively affects the performance of the common source amplifier in the same way (and has similar solutions).
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] When an AC signal is applied to the transistor amplifier it causes the base voltage VB to fluctuate in value at the AC signal.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The positive half of the applied signal will cause an increase in the value of VB this turn will increase the base current IB and cause a corresponding increase in emitter current IE and collector current IC.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] As a result, the collector emitter voltage will be reduced because of the increase voltage drop across RL.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The negative alternation of an AC signal will cause a decrease in IB this action then causes a corresponding decrease in IE through RL.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] It is also named common-emitter amplifier because the emitter of the transistor is common to both the input circuit and output circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The input signal is applied across the ground and the base circuit of the transistor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The output signal appears across ground and the collector of the transistor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Since the emitter is connected to the ground, it is common to signals, input and output.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The common-emitter circuit is the most widely used of junction transistor amplifiers.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] As compared with the common-base connection, it has higher input impedance and lower output impedance.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] A single power supply is easily used for biasing.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] In addition, higher voltage and power gains are usually obtained for common-emitter (CE) operation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Current gain in the common emitter circuit is obtained from the base and the collector circuit currents.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Because a very small change in base current produces a large change in collector current, the current gain (β) is always greater than unity for the common-emitter circuit, a typical value is about 50.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] A typical example of the use of a common-emitter amplifier is shown in Figure 3.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The input capacitor C removes any DC component of the input, and the resistors R1 and R2 bias the transistor so that it will remain in active mode for the entire range of the input.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] The output is an inverted copy of the AC component of the input that has been amplified by the ratio *R*C/*R*E and shifted by an amount determined by all four resistors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Because *R*C is often large, the output impedance of this circuit can be prohibitively high.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] To alleviate this problem, *R*C is kept as low as possible and the amplifier is followed by a voltage buffer like an emitter follower.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Common-emitter amplifiers are also used in radio frequency circuits, for example to amplify faint signals received by an antenna.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] In this case it is common to replace the load resistor with a tuned circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] This may be done to limit the bandwidth to a narrow band centered around the intended operating frequency.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] More importantly it also allows the circuit to operate at higher frequencies as the tuned circuit can be used to resonate any inter-electrode and stray capacitances, which normally limit the frequency response.
[src:decoupling-electronics/common-emitter] Common emitters are also commonly used as low-noise amplifiers.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] In electronics, electric power and telecommunication, **coupling** is the transfer of electrical energy from one circuit to another, or between parts of a circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] Coupling can be deliberate as part of the function of the circuit, or it may be undesirable, for instance due to coupling to stray fields.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] For example, energy is transferred from a power source to an electrical load by means of conductive coupling, which may be either resistive or direct coupling.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] An AC potential may be transferred from one circuit segment to another having a DC potential by use of a capacitor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] Electrical energy may be transferred from one circuit segment to another segment with different impedance by use of a transformer; this is known as impedance matching.
[src:decoupling-electronics/coupling-electronics] These are examples of electrostatic and electrodynamic inductive coupling.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] In electronics, a **decoupling capacitor** is a capacitor used to decouple (i.e. prevent electrical energy from transferring to) one part of a circuit from another.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing its effect on the rest of the circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] For higher frequencies, an alternative name is **bypass capacitor** as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high-impedance component of a circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Active devices of an electronic system (e.g. transistors, integrated circuits, vacuum tubes) are connected to their power supplies through conductors with finite resistance and inductance.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] If the current drawn by an active device changes, the voltage drop from the power supply to the device will also change due to these impedances.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor provides a bypass path for transient currents, instead of flowing through the common impedance.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The decoupling capacitor works as the device’s local energy storage.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor is placed between the power line and the ground to the circuit the current is to be provided.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] a voltage drop between a power line and the ground results in a current drawn out from the capacitor to the circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] When capacitance C is large enough, sufficient current is supplied to maintain an acceptable range of voltage drop.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor stores a small amount of energy that can compensate for the voltage drop in the power supply conductors to the capacitor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] To reduce undesired parasitic equivalent series inductance, small and large capacitors are often placed in parallel, adjacent to individual integrated circuits (see § Placement).
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] In digital circuits, decoupling capacitors also help prevent radiation of electromagnetic interference from relatively long circuit traces due to rapidly changing power supply currents.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Decoupling capacitors alone may not suffice in such cases as a high-power amplifier stage with a low-level pre-amplifier coupled to it.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Care must be taken in the layout of circuit conductors so that heavy current at one stage does not produce power supply voltage drops that affect other stages.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] This may require re-routing printed circuit board traces to segregate circuits, or the use of a ground plane to improve the stability of power supply.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor is often used to decouple a subcircuit from AC signals or voltage spikes on a power supply or other line.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor can shunt energy from those signals, or transients, past the subcircuit to be decoupled, right to the return path.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] For a power supply line, a bypass capacitor from the supply voltage line to the power supply return (neutral) would be used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] High frequencies and transient currents can flow through a capacitor to circuit ground instead of to the harder path of the decoupled circuit, but DC cannot go through the capacitor and continues to the decoupled circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Another kind of decoupling is stopping a portion of a circuit from being affected by switching that occurs in another portion of the circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Switching in subcircuit A may cause fluctuations in the power supply or other electrical lines, but you do not want subcircuit B, which has nothing to do with that switching, to be affected.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor can decouple subcircuits A and B so that B doesn't see any effects of the switching.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] In a subcircuit, switching will change the load current drawn from the source.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Typical power supply lines show inherent inductance, which results in a slower response to changes in current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The supply voltage will drop across these parasitic inductances for as long as the switching event occurs.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] This transient voltage drop would be seen by other loads as well if the inductance between two loads is much lower compared to the inductance between the loads and the output of the power supply.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] To decouple other subcircuits from the effect of the sudden current demand, a decoupling capacitor can be placed in parallel with the subcircuit, across its supply voltage lines.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] When switching occurs in the subcircuit, the capacitor supplies the transient current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Ideally, by the time the capacitor runs out of charge, the switching event has finished, so that the load can draw full current at normal voltage from the power supply and the capacitor can recharge.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The best way to reduce switching noise is to design a PCB as a giant capacitor by sandwiching the power and ground planes across a dielectric material.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Sometimes parallel combinations of capacitors are used to improve response.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] This is because real capacitors have parasitic inductance, which causes the impedance to deviate from that of an ideal capacitor at higher frequencies.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Transient load decoupling as described above is needed when there is a large load that gets switched quickly.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The parasitic inductance in every (decoupling) capacitor may limit the suitable capacity and influence the appropriate type if switching occurs very fast.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Logic circuits tend to do sudden switching (an ideal logic circuit would switch from low voltage to high voltage instantaneously, with no middle voltage ever observable).
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] So logic circuit boards often have a decoupling capacitor close to each logic IC connected from each power supply connection to a nearby ground.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors decouple every IC from every other IC in terms of supply voltage dips.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors are often placed at each power source as well as at each analog component in order to ensure that the supplies are as steady as possible.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Otherwise, an analog component with a poor power supply rejection ratio (PSRR) will copy fluctuations in the power supply onto its output.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] In these applications, the decoupling capacitors are often called *bypass capacitors* to indicate that they provide an alternate path for high-frequency signals that would otherwise cause the normally steady supply voltage to change.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Those components that require quick injections of current can *bypass* the power supply by receiving the current from the nearby capacitor.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Hence, the slower power supply connection is used to charge these capacitors, and the capacitors actually provide large quantities of high-availability current.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] A transient load decoupling capacitor is placed as close as possible to the device causing the transient.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] This minimizes the amount of line inductance and series resistance between the decoupling capacitor and the device.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] The longer the conductor between the capacitor and the device, the more inductance is present.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] Since capacitors differ in their high-frequency characteristics, decoupling commonly involves the use of a combination of capacitors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] For example in logic circuits, a common arrangement is ~100 nF ceramic per logic IC (multiple ones for complex ICs), combined with electrolytic or tantalum capacitor(s).
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-capacitor] These photos show old printed circuit boards with through-hole capacitors, where as modern boards typically have tiny surface-mount capacitors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] In electronics, **decoupling** is the prevention of undesired electrical energy transfer (coupling) between subsystems.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] A common example is connecting localized decoupling capacitors close to the power leads of integrated circuits to suppress coupling via the power supply connections.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] These act as a small localized energy reservoir that supply the circuit with current during transient, high current demand periods, preventing the voltage on the power supply rail from being pulled down by the momentary current load.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] Another common example of the use of decoupling capacitors is across the emitter bias resistor of transistor common emitter amplifiers to prevent the resistor absorbing a portion of the AC output power of the amplifier.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] Lossy ferrite beads may also be used to isolate or 'island' sections of circuitry.
[src:decoupling-electronics/decoupling-electronics] These add a high series impedance (in contrast to the low parallel impedance added by decoupling capacitors) to the power supply rails, preventing high-frequency currents being drawn from elsewhere in the system.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electrical energy is usually sold by the kilowatt-hour (1 kW·h = 3.6 MJ) which is the product of the power in kilowatts multiplied by running time in hours.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electric utilities measure energy using an electricity meter, which keeps a running total of the electrical energy delivered to a customer.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electric heating is an example of converting electrical energy into thermal energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] The simplest and most common type of electric heater uses electrical resistance to convert the energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] There are other ways to use electrical energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electric charges moves as a current the heater element which has a potential difference between the ends: energy is transferred from the charges to the element, increasing the element's temperature and thermal energy as the charges lose potential energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electricity generation is the process of generating electrical energy from other forms of energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] The fundamental principle of electricity generation was discovered during the 1820s and early 1830s by the British scientist Michael Faraday.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] His basic method is still used today: electric current is generated by the movement of a loop of wire, or disc of copper between the poles of a magnet.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] For electrical utilities, it is the first step in the delivery of electricity to consumers.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] The other processes, electricity transmission, distribution, and electrical energy storage and recovery using pumped-storage methods are normally carried out by the electric power industry.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] Electricity is most often generated at a power station by electromechanical generators, primarily driven by heat engines fueled by chemical combustion or nuclear fission but also by other means such as the kinetic energy of flowing water and wind.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electrical-energy] There are many other technologies that can be and are used to generate electricity such as solar photovoltaics and geothermal power.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic devices have significantly influenced the development of many aspects of modern society, such as telecommunications, entertainment, education, health care, industry, and security.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The main driving force behind the advancement of electronics is the semiconductor industry, which continually produces ever-more sophisticated electronic devices and circuits in response to global demand.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The semiconductor industry is one of the global economy's largest and most profitable industries, with annual revenues exceeding $481 billion in 2018.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The electronics industry also encompasses other branches that rely on electronic devices and systems, such as e-commerce, which generated over $29 trillion in online sales in 2017.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Practical applications started with the invention of the diode by Ambrose Fleming and the triode by Lee De Forest in the early 1900s, which made the detection of small electrical voltages, such as radio signals from a radio antenna, practicable.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The early growth of electronics was rapid, and by the 1920s, commercial radio broadcasting and telecommunications were becoming widespread and electronic amplifiers were being used in such diverse applications as long-distance telephony and the music recording industry.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The next big technological step took several decades to appear, when the first working point-contact transistor was invented by John Bardeen and Walter Houser Brattain at Bell Labs in 1947.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] However, vacuum tubes continued to play a leading role in the field of microwave and high power transmission as well as television receivers until the middle of the 1980s.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Since then, solid-state devices have all but completely taken over.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Vacuum tubes are still used in some specialist applications such as high power RF amplifiers, cathode-ray tubes, specialist audio equipment, guitar amplifiers and some microwave devices.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] In April 1955, the IBM 608 was the first IBM product to use transistor circuits without any vacuum tubes and is believed to be the first all-transistorized calculator to be manufactured for the commercial market.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The 608 contained more than 3,000 germanium transistors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Watson Jr. ordered all future IBM products to use transistors in their design.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] From that time on, transistors were almost exclusively used for computer logic circuits and peripheral devices.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] However, early junction transistors were relatively bulky devices that were difficult to manufacture on a mass-production basis, which limited them to a number of specialised applications.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] It was the first truly compact transistor that could be miniaturised and mass-produced for a wide range of uses.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Its advantages include high scalability, affordability, low power consumption, and high density.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] It revolutionized the electronics industry, becoming the most widely used electronic device in the world.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The MOSFET is the basic element in most modern electronic equipment.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] As the complexity of circuits grew, problems arose.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] One problem was the size of the circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] A complex circuit like a computer was dependent on speed.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] If the components were large, the wires interconnecting them must be long.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The electric signals took time to go through the circuit, thus slowing the computer.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The invention of the integrated circuit by Jack Kilby and Robert Noyce solved this problem by making all the components and the chip out of the same block (monolith) of semiconductor material.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The circuits could be made smaller, and the manufacturing process could be automated.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] This led to the idea of integrating all components on a single-crystal silicon wafer, which led to small-scale integration (SSI) in the early 1960s, and then medium-scale integration (MSI) in the late 1960s, followed by VLSI.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] In 2008, billion-transistor processors became commercially available.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] An electronic component is any component, either active or passive, in an **electronic system** or **electronic device**.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Components are connected together, usually by being soldered to a printed circuit board (PCB), to create an electronic circuit with a particular function.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Components may be packaged singly or in more complex groups as integrated circuits.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Passive electronic components are capacitors, inductors, resistors, whilst active components are such as semiconductor devices; transistors and thyristors, which control current flow at electron level.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic circuit functions can be divided into two function groups: analog and digital.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] A particular device may consist of circuitry that has either or a mix of the two types.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Analog circuits are becoming less common, as many of their functions are being digitized.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Analog circuits use a continuous range of voltage or current for signal processing, as opposed to the discrete levels used in digital circuits.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Analog circuits were common throughout electronic devices in the early years, in devices such as radio receivers and transmitters.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Analog electronic computers were valuable for solving problems with continuous variables until digital processing advanced.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Sometimes it may be difficult to classify some circuits that have elements of both linear and non-linear operation.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] An example is the voltage comparator, which receives a continuous range of voltage but only outputs one of two levels, as in a digital circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Similarly, an overdriven transistor amplifier can take on the characteristics of a controlled switch, having essentially two levels of output.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Analog circuits are still widely used for signal amplification, such as in the entertainment industry, and conditioning signals from analog sensors, such as in industrial measurement and control.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Digital circuits are electric circuits based on discrete voltage levels.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Digital circuits use Boolean algebra and are the basis of all digital computers and microprocessor devices.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] They range from simple logic gates to large integrated circuits, employing millions of such gates.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Digital circuits use a binary system with two voltage levels labelled *0* and *1* to indicate logical status.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Often logic *0* will be a lower voltage and referred to as *Low* while logic *1* is referred to as *High*.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] However, some systems use the reverse definition (*0* is *High*) or are current based.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Quite often, the logic designer may reverse these definitions from one circuit to the next as they see fit to facilitate their design.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The definition of the levels as *0* or *1* is arbitrary.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Ternary (with three states) logic has been studied, and some prototype computers made, but have not gained any significant practical acceptance.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Universally, computers and digital signal processors are constructed with digital logic circuits using transistors such as MOSFETs in the electronic logic gates to generate binary states.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic systems design deals with the multi-disciplinary design issues of complex electronic devices and systems, such as mobile phones and computers.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The subject covers a broad spectrum, from the design and development of an electronic system (new product development) to assuring its proper function, service life and disposal.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic systems design is therefore the process of defining and developing complex electronic devices to satisfy specified requirements of the user.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Due to the complex nature of electronics theory, laboratory experimentation is an important part of the development of electronic devices.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] These experiments are used to test or verify the engineer's design and detect errors.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Historically, electronics labs have consisted of electronics devices and equipment located in a physical space, although in more recent years the trend has been towards electronics lab simulation software, such as CircuitLogix, Multisim, and PSpice.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Today's electronics engineers have the ability to design circuits using premanufactured building blocks such as power supplies, semiconductors (i.e., semiconductor devices, such as transistors), and integrated circuits.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic design automation software programs include schematic capture programs and printed circuit board design programs.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Popular names in the EDA software world are NI Multisim, Cadence (ORCAD), EAGLE PCB and Schematic, Mentor (PADS PCB and LOGIC Schematic), Altium (Protel), LabCentre Electronics (Proteus), gEDA, KiCad and many others.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Heat generated by electronic circuitry must be dissipated to prevent immediate failure and improve long-term reliability.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Heat dissipation is mostly achieved by passive conduction/convection.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Means to achieve greater dissipation include heat sinks and fans for air cooling, and other forms of computer cooling such as water cooling.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] These techniques use convection, conduction, and radiation of heat energy.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electronic noise is defined as unwanted disturbances superposed on a useful signal that tend to obscure its information content.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Noise is not the same as signal distortion caused by a circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Noise is associated with all electronic circuits.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Noise may be electromagnetically or thermally generated, which can be decreased by lowering the operating temperature of the circuit.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Other types of noise, such as shot noise, cannot be removed as they are due to limitations in physical properties.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Many different methods of connecting components have been used over the years.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] For instance, early electronics often used point to point wiring with components attached to wooden breadboards to construct circuits.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Cordwood construction and wire wrap were other methods used.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Most modern-day electronics now use printed circuit boards made of materials such as FR-4 and FR-2.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Electrical components are generally mounted to PCBs using through-hole or surface mount.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Health and environmental concerns associated with electronics assembly have gained increased attention in recent years.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The electronics industry consists of various branches.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The central driving force behind the entire electronics industry is the semiconductor industry, which has annual sales of over $481 billion as of 2018.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The largest industry sector is e-commerce, which generated over $29 trillion in 2017.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] The most widely manufactured electronic device is the metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET), with an estimated 13 sextillion MOSFETs having been manufactured between 1960 and 2018.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] In the 1960s, U.S. manufacturers were unable to compete with Japanese companies such as Sony and Hitachi which could produce high-quality goods at lower prices.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] By the 1980s, however, U.S. manufacturers became the world leaders in semiconductor development and assembly.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] However, during the 1990s and subsequently, the industry shifted overwhelmingly to East Asia (a process begun with the initial movement of microchip mass-production there in the 1970s), as plentiful, cheap labor, and increasing technological sophistication, became widely available there.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Over three decades, the United States' global share of semiconductor manufacturing capacity fell, from 37% in 1990, to 12% in 2022.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] America's pre-eminent semiconductor manufacturer, Intel Corporation, fell far behind its subcontractor Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) in manufacturing technology.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] By that time, Taiwan had become the world's leading source of advanced semiconductors—followed by South Korea, the United States, Japan, Singapore, and China.
[src:decoupling-electronics/electronics] Important semiconductor industry facilities (which often are subsidiaries of a leading producer based elsewhere) also exist in Europe (notably the Netherlands), Southeast Asia, South America, and Israel.
